Pointers to Member Functions
In C++, a pointer to a member function (PMMF) is a special type of pointer that points to a non-static member function of a class. Unlike regular function pointers, PMMFs require an object of the class as an implicit argument, known as this. This object is used to disambiguate the member function call.

Declaring a Pointer to a Member Function
To declare a PMMF, use the following syntax:

	return_type (Classname::*member_function_pointer)(argument_types)

Replace:

	return_type: the return type of the member function
	Classname: the name of the class containing the member function
	member_function_pointer: the name of the PMMF
	argument_types: the types of the function’s arguments

Example:

	int (MyClass::*pmmf)(int, int);

This declares a PMMF pmmf that points to a member function of MyClass taking two int arguments and returning an int.

Initializing a Pointer to a Member Function
To initialize a PMMF, use the address-of operator & and the class name:

pmmf = &MyClass::member_function;

Replace member_function with the name of the member function you want to point to.

Calling a Member Function through a Pointer
To call a member function through a PMMF, use the object pointer and the ->* operator:

MyClass obj;
	(int (MyClass::*pmmf)(int, int)) obj_pmf = &MyClass::member_function;
	int result = (obj.*pmmf)(2, 3); // calls obj.member_function(2, 3)

Here, obj is an object of type MyClass, and pmmf is the PMMF pointing to the member_function. The (obj.*pmmf)(2, 3) expression calls the member function on obj with arguments 2 and 3.

Key Takeaways
	A PMMF requires an object of the class as an implicit argument (this).
	The PMMF declaration includes the class name and the function’s return and argument types.
	Initialize a PMMF using the address-of operator & and the class name.
	Call a member function through a PMMF using the object pointer and the ->* operator.
Example Code
Here’s a complete example demonstrating the use of a PMMF:

	#include <iostream>
	
	class MyClass {
	public:
	    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
	    int subtract(int a, int b) { return a - b; }
	};
	
	int main() {
	    MyClass obj;
	    int (MyClass::*pmmf)(int, int) = &MyClass::add;
	
	    int result = (obj.*pmmf)(2, 3); // calls obj.add(2, 3)
	    std::cout << "Result: " << result << std::endl;
	
	    pmmf = &MyClass::subtract;
	    result = (obj.*pmmf)(4, 2); // calls obj.subtract(4, 2)
	    std::cout << "Result: " << result << std::endl;
	
	    return 0;
	}

This example demonstrates the declaration, initialization, and usage of a PMMF to call member functions of MyClass.